Animated. A weathered scroll on a table, near a lit candle and old-fashioned globe. The scroll reads: I, Lemuel Gulliver give thee a faithful history of my most interesting adventure in the south sea. On the 5th day of November, 1699, having reached latitude 30 degrees, two minutes south, a storm of great fury suddenly... 

Lightning flashes; the candle blows out. 


A stormy, dark ocean. A lone sailor in shirtsleeves clings to a rope on a wave-battered ship. He is washed overboard by an immense swell. The sailor struggles to keep his head above the crashing waters, reaching for splinters of the destroyed vessel. 

***

Only his head and hands are kept above water as he flounders under wave after wave.

Finally, he emerges onto a beach, the lightning in the distance. He stumbles from the surf and falls facedown as the tide washes over him. His shoulder length dark hair obscures his face as he lies, gasping for air.

The sailor hoists himself up and staggers several more steps away from the water before finally falling on his side. He rolls onto his back with his arms by his sides, one leg propped up, and breathes heavily.

*** 

-All's well!

A pinpoint of light bobs in the distance.

-All's well!

result.description:
Gulliver's Travels is a 1939 American cel-animated Technicolor feature film, directed by Dave Fleischer and produced by Max Fleischer for Fleischer Studios. The film was released on December 22, 1939 by Paramount Pictures, who had the feature produced as an answer to the success of Walt Disney's box-office hit Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs. The sequences for the film were directed by Seymour Kneitel, Willard Bowsky, Tom Palmer, Grim Natwick, William Henning, Roland Crandall, Thomas Johnson, Robert Leffingwell, Frank Kelling, Winfield Hoskins, and Orestes Calpini. This is Paramount's first feature-length animated film.

More informations: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gulliver's_Travels_(1939_film)

IMDb: http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0031397/

The film is in public domain: http://publicdomainreview.org/2012/01/22/gullivers-travels-1939/
